                {
                    "content": "<style type=\"text/css\"> @import url(\"https://www.bbassets.com/static/froala_style_v2.min.css\"); </style>\n        <div style=\"font-family: 'ProximaNova-Regular';font-size:13px;line-height: 18px;color:8f8f8f;\">\n            <p>In the rich tapestry of Indian cuisine, coconut holds a cherished place as a versatile ingredient. Known as \"Nariyal,\" it is integral to regional dishes across the subcontinent. Coconut's sweet, nutty flavour and creamy texture feature prominently in both savoury and sweet preparations. From coconut chutneys in South India to coconut-based curries in coastal regions, its flesh, milk, and oil enhance dishes with richness and depth. Coconut is also used in desserts like laddoos and barfis, showcasing its culinary versatility. Beyond food, coconut plays a cultural role in rituals, festivals, and everyday life, symbolising prosperity, and purity in Indian traditions.</p>\n        </div>",
